The '''automotive industry Massachusetts''' refers to a period of time from 1893 to 1989 when automobiles were manufactured in the Commonwealth of [[Massachusetts]] commercially. During this time, the state produced more automobiles than [[Detroit, Michigan]].<ref name=Kennedy>{{cite news|last=Kennedy|first=George|title=Boston Cup celebrates cars made in Mass.|url=http://www.boston.com/cars/news-and-reviews/2013/09/13/boston-cup-celebrates-cars-made-mass/4Ff5x9H111eQYz9FMQtoII/story.html|accessdate=22 December 2013|newspaper=[[The Boston Globe]]|date=13 September 2013}}</ref>

==History==
===Early years===
On September 20, 1893, [[Charles Duryea|Charles]] and [[J. Frank Duryea|Frank Duryea]] of [[Springfield, Massachusetts]] built and then road-tested the first-ever American, [[gasoline]]-powered [[automobile|car]] in Springfield.<ref name="inventors.about.com">{{cite web|url=http://inventors.about.com/od/dstartinventors/a/DuryeaBrothers.htm |title=The Duryea Brothers - Automobile History |publisher=Inventors.about.com |date=2010-09-16 |accessdate=2013-12-22}}</ref> The [[Duryea Motor Wagon Company]] was built on the third floor of the [[Stacy Building]] in Springfield, and first publicly road-tested on Howard Bemis's farm.<ref>http://hampdendeedsnews.blogspot.com/2010_05_01_archive.html</ref><ref>[http://www.autoswalk.com/news/article/10/21.html Worlds Greatest Cars]. {{dead link|date=July 2011}}</ref> During these years, many independent manufacturers built automobiles in the state.<ref name=Kennedy />

In 1900, Springfield was joined by [[Skene (automobile)|Skene]], and [[Knox Automobile]], which survived until 1927 as manufacturers of automobiles.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.arcadiapublishing.com/mm5/merchant.mvc?Screen=PROD&Product_Code=9780738504995&Store_Code=arcadia&search=MA&offset=0&filter_cat=&PowerSearch_Begin_Only=&sort=code.asc&range_low=&range_high=%20%26srch_state%3D1 |title=Knox Automobile Company |publisher=Arcadia Publishing |date= |accessdate=2012-04-04}}</ref>  In 1905, Knox famously produced America's first motorized [[fire engine]]s for Springfield's Fire Department <U+2013> the first modern fire department in the world.<ref name="springfield375.org">{{cite web|url=http://springfield375.org/?p=126 |title=Firsts &#124; Springfield 375 |publisher=Springfield375.org |date= |accessdate=2013-12-22}}</ref> In the 1920s, [[Rolls-Royce America]] decided to also start manufacturing in the city, stating, "The artisans of Springfield <U+2013> from long experience in fine precision work <U+2013> were found to possess the same pride in workmanship as the craftsmen of England." From 1921 until 1931, the company's only foreign plant was located in Springfield, off of Hendee Street. It assembled nearly three thousand [[Rolls-Royce Silver Ghost|Silver Ghosts]] and [[Rolls-Royce Phantom I|Phantoms]].<ref>[http://web.archive.org/web/20041209073336/http://www.rolls-royce.com/northamerica/history/default.htm Rolls-Royce History]. Retrieved 2013-12-22.</ref> The Rolls-Royce factory is adjacent to the former Indian Motorcycle manufacturing plant, by [[American International College]].

On the Eastern side of the state, the [[Ford Motor Company]] opened the [[Cambridge Assembly]] in 1913, and manufactured vehicles there until 1926, when it opened the [[Somerville Assembly]].<ref name=History>{{cite web|title=Building History- 640 Memorial Drive|url=http://www.640memorialdrive.com/property-history.html|accessdate=22 December 2013}}</ref><ref name=Somerville>{{cite web|title=Squares and Neighborhoods - Assembly Square|url=http://www.somervillema.gov/departments/ospcd/squares-and-neighborhoods/assembly-square|publisher=City of Somerville|accessdate=22 December 2013}}</ref>

===Great Depression and World War II===
The [[Great Depression]] ended up closing many plants nationally. In Springfield, [[Rolls-Royce America]] decided to close their plant rather than retool it.<ref>[http://web.archive.org/web/20041209073336/http://www.rolls-royce.com/northamerica/history/default.htm Rolls-Royce History]. Retrieved 2013-12-22.</ref> During the war years, it is not known what the [[Somerville Assembly]] produced

===Post-war years===
During the post-war years, manufacturing boomed in the state. [[General Motors]] opened the [[Framingham Assembly]] in 1947. In 1958, the [[Somerville Assembly]] was closed Ford, following the failure of the [[Ford Edsel]].<ref name=Somerville /> 

===End of manufacturing===
In 1983, General Motors, decided to idle then later shutter the plant, citing its small size and issues with town leaders.<ref name="globe-1">{{cite news |title=GM to Close Framingham Plant |last=Patterson |first=Gregory A. |date=February 4, 1987|work=The Boston Globe |pages=A1 |accessdate=22 December 2013}}</ref><ref name="globe-2">{{cite news |title=The two faces of Tony Colonna |last=Beam |first=Alex |date=November 15, 1987 |work=The Boston Globe |pages=A1 |accessdate=22 December 2013}}</ref><ref name="globe-3">{{cite news |title=GM to Close Framingham Plant Nov. 30 3, 700 to be put out of work |last=Kranish |first=Michael |coauthors=Bruce Mohl |date=November 5, 1987 |work=The Boston Globe |pages=A1 |accessdate=22 December 2013}}</ref> The plant was later closed in 1989, bringing to an end of 106 years of commercial car manufacturing.

